Content:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pathlib
import sys
from xml.dom import minidom
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd



def distance(city, stations):
    city_lat = city['latitude']
    city_lon = city['longitude']

    #Code was structured from this link that was in the assignment
    #https://stackoverflow.com/questions/27928/calculate-distance-between-two-latitude-longitude-points-haversine-formula/21623206

    
    p = np.pi/180
    a = 0.5 - np.cos((city_lat-stations['latitude'])*p)/2 + np.cos(stations['latitude'] * p) * np.cos(city_lat*p) * (1-np.cos((city_lon - stations['longitude']) *p))/2
    final_result = 6371 * 2 * np.arcsin(np.sqrt(a))

    return final_result


def best_tmax(city, stations):
    distance_city = distance(city, stations)

    
    index_holder = np.argmin(distance_city)
    
    temp = stations.iloc[index_holder]['avg_tmax']
    temp_series = pd.Series({'avg_tmax':temp})  
    city = city.append(temp_series)

    return city
    

stations_file = pathlib.Path(sys.argv[1])
city_file = pathlib.Path(sys.argv[2])

cities = pd.read_csv(city_file)
stations = pd.read_json(stations_file, lines=True)
stations['avg_tmax'] = stations['avg_tmax']/10
cities = cities.dropna()
cities['area'] = cities['area']/(1000 * 1000)

cities = cities[cities['area'] < 10000].reset_index()
cities = cities.drop(columns = ['index'])
cities = cities.set_index('name')



#print(stations.iloc[best_tmax(cities.iloc[0], stations)]['station'])

cities = cities.apply(best_tmax, stations = stations,axis = 1)


pop_area = cities['population']/cities['area']


plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5)) # change the size to something sensible
plt.plot(cities['avg_tmax'], pop_area, 'b.', alpha = 0.5)
plt.xlabel('Avg Max Temperature (\u00b0C)')
plt.ylabel('Population Density (people/km\u00b2)')
plt.title('Temperature vs Population Density')
plt.show()
